summary:
Namjoon - You want to give up on your dreams
Even from across the room, Namjoon can tell that there’s something wrong with you....
body:
Namjoon - You want to give up on your dreams

Even from across the room, Namjoon can tell that there’s something wrong with you. There’s something about the way you’re sat, the way you’re holding yourself, that sets off alarms in Namjoon’s head. He’d invited you over to the dorm to watch some movies, but this is clearly more important.

Your eyes are glazed over, and you’re barely focussing. You’re not in the mood, but you didn’t want to let Namjoon down. You can’t help it, though - you’ve had a rough week, and unfortunately a few movies won’t fix that, no matter how many snacks Namjoon prepared,

“Right, spill it,” Namjoon says a while later, when you’re about half way through the first film. He pauses it and turns to look at you with a pointed expression. It takes you a few seconds to even realise that he was talking to you, but when you do you don’t responds. You just look at Namjoon with a confused expression, “I’m serious. Something is obviously bothering you, so you need to tell me. You can’t just sit there and mope for the rest of your life,” Namjoon continues, half serious and half joking. You sigh and shake your head, not really wanting to share.

It takes about 5 minutes for Namjoon to persuade you otherwise,

“I know it seems stupid, but… I just don’t know, I look up to him so much and he literally turned around and said I won’t ever make it. I don’t even want to go back anymore, I’ll just work in my parent’s coffee shop,” You sigh. You’d been told basically to give up on your dreams today, and it hurt. It was even worse since you looked up to the person like nothing else. It’s really gotten you down, and the thought of continuing to pursue it now just doesn’t sit right with you. What’s the point?

Namjoon remains silent for a few seconds, not quite sure what to say. He can’t believe that anyone in a position of authority would say that to you, knowing full well how it could affect you. His eyebrows pull together as he gathers his thoughts,

“Why are you letting that stop you? I’ve seen how amazing you are, and I also see how amazing you will be if you keep working. One comment shouldn’t stop you,” Namjoon starts, already seeing your sceptical expression. He knows a quick pep talk from him won’t fix it, but it’s worth a try, “I think what you should do is refuse to give up. Wouldn’t the biggest middle finger ever be getting to the top of your field and showing him he was wrong? There’s no way you can just give up now. It’s been years that you’ve been working for it, and I can’t stand the thought of you spending the rest of your life as a barista! It’s not what you want,” Namjoon all but whines, trying to keep his voice mature,

“I’m just not sure,” You murmur, still uncertain. But Namjoon words do ring some truth in your heart. Maybe you could just give it some thought - maybe you shouldn’t give up just yet, even if you want to, “I’ll think about it, and decide later,” You assure him, and Namjoon’s face lights up. That’s good enough for now.

Masterlist

I don’t even want to go back anymore, I’ll just work in my parent’s coffee shop,” You sigh. You’d been told basically to give up on your dreams today, and it hurt. It was even worse since you looked up to the person like nothing else. It’s really gotten you down, and the thought of continuing to pursue it now just doesn’t sit right with you. What’s the point?

Namjoon remains silent for a few seconds, not quite sure what to say. He can’t believe that anyone in a position of authority would say that to you, knowing full well how it could affect you. His eyebrows pull together as he gathers his thoughts,

“Why are you letting that stop you? I’ve seen how amazing you are, and I also see how amazing you will be if you keep working. One comment shouldn’t stop you,” Namjoon starts, already seeing your sceptical expression. He knows a quick pep talk from him won’t fix it, but it’s worth a try, “I think what you should do is refuse to give up. Wouldn’t the biggest middle finger ever be getting to the top of your field and showing him he was wrong? There’s no way you can just give up now. It’s been years that you’ve been working for it, and I can’t stand the thought of you spending the rest of your life as a barista! It’s not what you want,” Namjoon all but whines, trying to keep his voice mature,

“I’m just not sure,” You murmur, still uncertain. But Namjoon words do ring some truth in your heart. Maybe you could just give it some thought - maybe you shouldn’t give up just yet, even if you want to, “I’ll think about it, and decide later,” You assure him, and Namjoon’s face lights up. That’s good enough for now.
